Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Japanese encephalitis (JE) cases continue to increase this year (2020) in Assam state, from 38 cases and 5 deaths reported on 9 Jul 2020, 184 cases and 24 deaths as of 22 Jul 2020, to at least 199 cases and 29 deaths on 27 Jul 2020, and now 318 cases with 51 deaths mentioned above. Interestingly, there is no mention of cases of acute encephalitis syndrome (AES) in the report above, which have been more frequent than JE cases in the previous reports from Assam this year (2020).

Although mosquito control is not mentioned in the report above as a JE preventive measure, it is difficult to effectively accomplish in localities where the JE virus vectors -- _Culex_ spp. -- are abundant and widespread. Because the _Culex_ vector mosquitoes also breed in rice paddies, which may be extensive, vector control over large areas is difficult. The reduction in cases and deaths is attributed to vaccination and behavioral changes that have reduced exposure to vector mosquitoes. Vaccination is the most effective measure to prevent JE virus infection.

Map of India: http://www.mapsofindia.com/maps/india/india-political-map.htm. - Mod.TY

